```
function commonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  let result = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < arr2.length; j++) {
      if (arr1[i] === arr2[j]) {
        result.push(arr1[i]);
        break;
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```
This function uses two inner loops to look each element in `arr1` and match it with each element in `arr2`. When the match is found, the result is pushed into the `result` array.

 note that the `break` keyword is used in the second loop to break the loop as soon as a match is found, so that the loop only runs twice for each element in `arr1`.

Here's an example usage of this function:
```
let arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
let arr2 = [3, 4, 5, 6, 7];

commonElements(arr1, arr2).should === [3, 4, 5];
```
This will result in the common elements found in both arrays being `3`, `4`, and `5`.

